# Normalize line endings across platforms.
#
# `text=auto eol=lf` tells git: auto-detect text vs. binary, and for any text
# file, force LF in BOTH the working tree and the index — overriding each
# developer's `core.autocrlf` setting. This is what makes the line-ending
# rule a property of the repo, not the workstation.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Windows scripts are the exception — cmd.exe is fine with LF on modern
# Windows but most editors and lint tools still emit CRLF for these, and
# some legacy contexts (older PowerShell, batch wrappers) genuinely need it.
# Keeping them as CRLF avoids surprise breakage.
*.bat   text eol=crlf
*.cmd   text eol=crlf
*.ps1   text eol=crlf

# Explicit binary declarations. `text=auto` already protects most of these
# via auto-detection, but spelling them out documents intent and removes any
# ambiguity for unusual file shapes (e.g. a corrupted UTF-16 BOM that gets
# misclassified as text).
*.png   binary
*.jpg   binary
*.jpeg  binary
*.gif   binary
*.webp  binary
*.avif  binary
*.ico   binary
*.svg   text
*.pdf   binary
*.woff  binary
*.woff2 binary
*.ttf   binary
*.otf   binary
*.eot   binary
*.zip   binary
*.tar   binary
*.tar.gz binary
*.gz    binary
*.mp4   binary
*.mp3   binary
*.wav   binary
*.webm  binary
